Refactor the `sendMessage` handler in apps/api/src/chat/chat.controller.ts to forward the streaming Response to the client:

- ADD imports: `Res` from '@nestjs/common', `Response as ExpressResponse` from 'express'
- REMOVE the import of `SendMessageResponse` from './dto/send-message-response.dto' if no other handler still uses it
- Update the `sendMessage` handler signature:
  ```
  @Post('sessions/:sessionId/messages')
  async sendMessage(
    @Param('sessionId', ParseMongoIdPipe) sessionId: string,
    @Body() dto: CreateChatMessageDto,
    @Res() res: ExpressResponse,
  ): Promise<void> {
    const streamResponse = await this.chatService.sendMessage(sessionId, dto);

    res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/event-stream');
    res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'no-cache');
    res.setHeader('Connection', 'keep-alive');

    if (!streamResponse.body) {
      res.end();
      return;
    }

    const reader = streamResponse.body.getReader();
    try {
      while (true) {
        const { done, value } = await reader.read();
        if (done) break;
        res.write(value);
      }
    } finally {
      reader.releaseLock();
      res.end();
    }
  }
  ```
- Keep all other handlers (`createSession`, `listSessions`, `listMessages`) and the `@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard)` decorator UNCHANGED.

IMPORTANT: NestJS bypasses the framework's response serialization when `@Res()` is used directly, which is exactly what we want here for streaming. Do NOT add `@HttpCode` to this handler — the AI SDK Response already returns 200.

